Inferno

Target IP: 10.10.93.38

Scanning


Performing a scan against this machine shows a huge number of TCP ports open. I will focus on the main TCP ports: SSH, FTP, and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP


The webpage above is displayed for this application. The content of the text is not in English.


Doing a directory search using the command gobuster dir -u http://10.10.93.38/ -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-lowercase-2.3-medium.txt -x php,html,txt shows there is a directory called /inferno.


The page /inferno requires username and password. I used cewl on the main page to extract the possible passwords. When I sprayed this with the user dante against SSH and /infero page, I had no luck. However, trying admin with the rockyou.txt worked! I got the credential admin:dante1.


After logging in, the webpage above is displayed. I sprayed default credential of Codiad but I had no luck. However, reusing the same credential of admin:dante1 worked!


Now I have access to the Codiad application running on the target machine. After some further enumeration, I notice I do not have the permission to change the project files. Obtaining the version of this application is hard. However, there is an RCE exploit for this application.

Exploitation


I made a copy of the exploit above. Time to run it against the target machine.


And now I have a foothold on the target machine. In the picture above, the terminal on top is where I used the exploit. The middle terminal is used to setup the reverse shell. And the bottom terminal is where I gain a reverse shell from the target machine with the session as www-data.

Privilege Escalation


The reverse shell automatically disconnects after a minute, so I have to be quick. I found an interesting file called .download.dat which is in hexadecimal.


After converting the hexadecimal to ASCII, I received the message above on the right. This message contains dante:V1rg1l10h3lpm3. Is this the SSH login for dante?


And using the credential above against SSH worked.


I can use this binary to write over the /etc/passwd file.


I gained a root shell by creating a new user with root privileges. The command I used to create the password root is openssl passwd root. Then I used su to switch user to rooter.
